               <head>Lubb al-tavarikh</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Lubb al-tavārīkh by Qazvīnī, Yaḥyá ibn ʻAbd al-Laṭīf, 1481-1555</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85068446 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85148202" n="1" xml:id="Uk_Or_15920-item1">
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied" key="viaf_81154149">Qazvīnī, Yaḥyá ibn ʻAbd al-Laṭīf, 1481-1555</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="per" type="supplied" key="viaf_81154149">قزوينى، يحيى بن عبد اللطيف</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_3495">Lubb al-tavārīkh</title>
                     <title xml:lang="per" key="work_3495">لب التواريخ
</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>A summary account of  Islamic and Iranian history down to 948/1542, dedicated to the Safavid prince Abū l-Fatḥ Bahrām Mīrzā, fourth son of Shah Ismā‘īl, by Mīr Yaḥyà ibn ‘Abd al-Laṭīf al-Qazvīnī (d. 962/1555). Comprises four sections (qism). 
</p>
                        <p>
For this work, manuscripts and partial translations, see Storey PL I/1 pp. 111-13; more detailed is Storey/Bregel’ PL I, pp. 399-403. See also Elliot and Dowson, History of India, IV, pp. 293-7. Lubb al-tavārīkh was published at Bombay (Mumbai) in 1302/1884 and at Tehran in 1314/1936. 

Other BL copies: Or. 140, Add. 16707, Add. 23512, and Add. 6541 f. 9-127 (see BM I, 104-5; II, 797); I.O. Islamic 526, 1986, 3394 and (a fragment) 61 (see IO I cols. 31-2, 37).
</p>
                        <p>Other contents: a small number of brief marginalia throughout: ff 68v-73v, Z̲ikr-i aḥvālāt-i Abū Naṣr-i Fārābī: notes on the philosopher al-Fārābī (4th/10th century); 73v-84v, Guftār dar ba‘żī-yi aḥvālāt-i Shaykh al-Ra’īs Abū ‘Alī-i Sīnā, nuskhha-’i ṣaḥīḥ dar dast āvardam nivishtam kih dar nazd-i ahl-i sayr makhfī namā[na]d: on the polymath Ibn Sīnā (d. 428/1037); front flyleaf, label with title, author, and number 227; several erased seal impressions on various folios, e.g. 127r.</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per">Persian</textLang>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
